WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.440
 So now we're gonna take a quick look at URL mapping

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:04.200
 and URL reversing.

00:00:04.200 --> 00:00:06.760
 This has to do with basically routing,

00:00:06.760 --> 00:00:10.080
 and it really allows us to generate links

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:11.500
 from one page to another.

00:00:11.500 --> 00:00:12.800
 So we're in the middle of a page,

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:14.760
 and we wanna make a link to a different page.

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:17.260
 We gotta figure out what the string of that is.

00:00:17.260 --> 00:00:21.100
 So again, we're sitting here in the middle of our code,

00:00:21.100 --> 00:00:22.480
 we're in the views,

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:26.640
 and this URL mapping is basically a set of functions

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:29.680
 that allow us to read the urls.py.

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:31.800
 In a way, if all these functions didn't exist

00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:34.040
 that allowed us to read urls.py,

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:35.800
 we would write a bunch of functions to do that,

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:37.720
 and so these are just now part of Django.

00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:40.840
 And so often these are used in the view.

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:41.900
 Sometimes they're actually used

00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:44.400
 right inside urls.py to come up.

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:47.280
 So it's like, if you know the name of a view,

00:00:47.280 --> 00:00:48.960
 what would be the URL to get to that view?

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:51.080
 And sometimes views have just a URL,

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:53.380
 and sometimes they're a URL plus a parameter,

00:00:53.380 --> 00:00:55.160
 and that's all set up here.

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:59.160
 And so it's like, give me a link to a view, please.

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:02.040
 And then Django looks in the urls.py,

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:04.000
 potentially across the applications,

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:05.400
 and gives you that string.

00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:07.920
 And it's just to avoid hard coding the strings.

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:10.040
 It's really the idea.

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:11.540
 And so this is just a common problem.

00:01:11.540 --> 00:01:14.480
 This is the documentation right from the Django website.

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:15.800
 You don't wanna hard code these things.

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:19.720
 You actually can, but then if you rename an application,

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:21.680
 the whole idea is you could make a Django project

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:24.160
 that had four or five applications,

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:25.320
 and then you could reuse some of those

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:26.400
 in a different Django project

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:27.560
 and add some more applications.

00:01:27.560 --> 00:01:30.160
 So you don't want these applications

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:33.760
 to have too many hard coded decisions.

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:36.720
 And it might be easier to hard code some of these things,

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:41.160
 but it is actually, in the long run,

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:42.960
 much easier from a maintenance perspective.

00:01:42.960 --> 00:01:45.320
 And so it's just a, it's better maintenance.

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:47.980
 It's another don't repeat yourself,

00:01:47.980 --> 00:01:50.760
 or doing a table lookup rather than hard coding strings.

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:53.680
 It also lets you hunt around in your code

00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:55.280
 to see where it is that you're talking

00:01:55.280 --> 00:01:56.640
 to that other application.

00:01:56.640 --> 00:01:58.080
 'Cause we're gonna do login eventually,

00:01:58.080 --> 00:01:59.400
 and login is another place.

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:00.920
 It's not in our application,

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:03.660
 but our application is gonna have to generate login URLs

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:05.200
 by asking the login application,

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:07.240
 hey, what's the URL to log in?

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:08.680
 What's the URL to log out?

00:02:08.680 --> 00:02:11.400
 And that's where we'll mostly start doing this.

00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:12.520
 So I wanna talk about it now,

00:02:12.520 --> 00:02:14.360
 so when we get to log in and log out,

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:16.320
 you'll have that make more sense to you.

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:19.060
 And it also is some of the stuff that you're doing

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:22.960
 from the tutorials, you're putting these reverse

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:25.320
 lookup things in, and you may or may not know what they are.

00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:27.400
 And my goal here is to give you a little sense

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:29.640
 of what really they're there for.

00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:31.600
 So let's take a look at an example.

00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:35.160
 So here we have our urls.py, and most of it,

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:36.560
 I mean, this is the application route,

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:37.760
 so if you're looking in the samples,

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:39.280
 it's in the route application.

00:02:39.280 --> 00:02:41.860
 The main thing that we've added is some names.

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:45.080
 Names are here to look up these paths.

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:47.400
 We don't really wanna look it up by this path mapping,

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:49.040
 'cause that could actually change.

00:02:49.040 --> 00:02:53.400
 So we're basically saying this view in your views.py,

00:02:53.400 --> 00:02:56.240
 second view, is gonna be referenceable

00:02:56.240 --> 00:02:57.840
 by this second dash view.

00:02:57.840 --> 00:03:00.600
 I named them differently very much on purpose.

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:04.800
 So here's what happens if you just go to the route/route,

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:07.320
 the name of my application.

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:10.400
 It pulls up this main/html, and so the first thing

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:14.040
 I wanna show you is what a hard-coded URL looks like.

00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:16.640
 Now we know that, blah, blah, blah,

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:20.680
 samples/route/second is gonna go to that second view,

00:03:20.680 --> 00:03:22.240
 'cause the application's name is route,

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:25.640
 and the view name is second, and that's good.

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:27.600
 That will work, it's not gonna break,

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:29.260
 but this is where you lose flexibility

00:03:29.260 --> 00:03:31.240
 as you try to recombine the applications

00:03:31.240 --> 00:03:32.960
 from one end to the other.

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:37.100
 And so in a sense, what we're asking to do here

00:03:37.100 --> 00:03:39.980
 is we're going to instead use this URL utility,

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:44.600
 and so in our template, we use curly brace percent,

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:46.720
 and then we're running a utility

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:49.840
 that's been plugged into the template system

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:53.040
 that is like, when we're running the URL function,

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:55.440
 as it were, and we're gonna pass a string to it,

00:03:55.440 --> 00:03:58.240
 and that is, within the route application,

00:03:58.240 --> 00:03:59.800
 the view that is named second view.

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:04.000
 So that goes into this file, routeurls.py,

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.560
 read down the views until it finds second view,

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:11.560
 and then it reverse-generates the path that works for that.

00:04:11.560 --> 00:04:14.560
 Now in this case, these two strings are gonna be the same,

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:18.760
 and yes, that looks a little uglier,

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:21.240
 but the key is that we can make changes here,

00:04:21.240 --> 00:04:24.680
 and this will not, the top one, route/second,

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:26.180
 will not reflect the changes,

00:04:26.180 --> 00:04:27.600
 but if we're looking it up by name,

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:29.480
 we can do all kinds of crazy things

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:32.500
 and remap stuff quite naturally.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:35.160
 And so again, it's just this URL command,

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:39.500
 the name of the view, the application, colon, the view.

00:04:39.500 --> 00:04:42.400
 So this is what it looks like when it's all said and done.

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:44.040
 There's no parameters to this,

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:45.780
 so if you take a look at this,

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:49.440
 this route/second view ends up under this hard-coded,

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:51.800
 the route/second view, the hard-coded ones,

00:04:51.800 --> 00:04:54.360
 ends up under the string in the URL output,

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:55.600
 I mean the page output.

00:04:55.600 --> 00:05:00.740
 We just see the, it's /route/first is the thing

00:05:00.740 --> 00:05:03.640
 that comes out from running the code URL

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:05.560
 and passing route colon first view in,

00:05:05.560 --> 00:05:07.040
 so that's what it looks up.

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:11.520
 And we can make a link, this is now in a href,

00:05:11.520 --> 00:05:16.220
 and the actual path is sitting there in the href.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:18.800
 So now we're going to see how we do this

00:05:18.800 --> 00:05:20.920
 when we're going from one application to another.

00:05:20.920 --> 00:05:24.200
 So an application we're gonna look at in just a bit

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:25.920
 is this thing called the generic views,

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:28.040
 it's application called gview.

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:30.120
 And we wanna make a link to that application,

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:31.900
 and we know that there are two views,

00:05:31.900 --> 00:05:34.120
 there's a list view and a detail view,

00:05:34.120 --> 00:05:38.880
 and all we have to do is go take a look at the urls.py,

00:05:38.880 --> 00:05:41.300
 and we know that it's an application,

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:43.760
 it's an application gview, and there's a,

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:46.040
 this view has a name and that view has a name.

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:49.760
 The view that is all the cats has got a name of cats,

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:53.080
 and the view for a single cat is cat.

00:05:53.080 --> 00:05:56.600
 But the cat one takes a parameter, it's an integer number,

00:05:56.600 --> 00:05:59.800
 which is cat number 42 or whatever.

00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:02.840
 And so we're sitting here in the route application,

00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:05.500
 route application, main.html,

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:08.240
 and we can now go create a URL

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:11.600
 that actually is pointing to another application

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:13.920
 and a view within that other application.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:16.680
 So this is a URL for gview cats,

00:06:16.680 --> 00:06:18.280
 and that'll just look it up.

00:06:18.280 --> 00:06:21.400
 So now we don't even have to know what the URL patterns are

00:06:21.400 --> 00:06:24.140
 inside of gview/cats.

00:06:24.140 --> 00:06:28.320
 Now, we can look at gview cat, which is this URL,

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:30.120
 but you'll notice that this has a parameter,

00:06:30.120 --> 00:06:32.280
 and so we actually have to add a second parameter,

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:33.960
 which is that 42 number.

00:06:33.960 --> 00:06:36.160
 And so this will generate the URL straight

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:39.520
 to the detail page for a single cat.

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:41.960
 Now, there's a lot of nice stuff about this.

00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:44.200
 So for example, if you omit this,

00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:47.160
 it's going to look this gview cat up and find it

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:49.160
 and say, you know what, I'm supposed to have an integer.

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:52.320
 And it'll blow up on you, right, if you get that wrong.

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:55.880
 Or if you put a 42 on this one, on the gview cats,

00:06:55.880 --> 00:06:57.760
 you're not supposed to have a number on that.

00:06:57.760 --> 00:06:59.860
 But gview cat, you are supposed to have a number.

00:06:59.860 --> 00:07:03.360
 So this is one of the nice things about this reverse URL

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:07.080
 lookup, in that we can, there's some error checking

00:07:07.080 --> 00:07:10.200
 that goes on, 'cause if it could just blow up silently,

00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:12.340
 and in many ways, when the code blows up silently,

00:07:12.340 --> 00:07:15.480
 it's worse than blowing up in a spectacular fashion.

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:17.940
 'Cause if it blows up in a spectacular fashion,

00:07:17.940 --> 00:07:19.020
 you can fix it.

00:07:19.020 --> 00:07:22.720
 So this is what it looks like.

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:26.880
 So this gview cats URL and gview cat 42,

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:28.680
 this one that actually is the detail page

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:33.120
 that demands a parameter, it constructs that just fine.

00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:38.120
 Okay, so that's going from the route application

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:42.800
 to the gview application.

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:46.600
 Now, you can also, this is kind of subtle,

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:49.400
 and we will need it when we start doing social login

00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:50.600
 using GitHub.

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:53.600
 So I'll just mention it, 'cause we're deep in it right now.

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:58.360
 And so basically, this is actually the overall

00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:00.960
 dj4e-samples-urls.py, and that's the one

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:02.480
 that's pulling all the URLs together,

00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:05.440
 kind of in the same folder as settings.py.

00:08:05.440 --> 00:08:08.580
 And so you're pulling in a bunch of URLs,

00:08:08.580 --> 00:08:11.400
 and these live in an application of their own name,

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:14.700
 but we can actually give them a name of our own

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:15.540
 to reference them.

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:18.200
 So you can actually name them, you can reference them

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:20.200
 with the name they were already given

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:22.320
 by the application that we're talking to,

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:24.200
 or we can say, you know what, I'm gonna call these

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:27.020
 social colon, or nsroute colon.

00:08:27.020 --> 00:08:29.180
 So if we take this route application

00:08:29.180 --> 00:08:32.440
 and include all those URLs, and we're gonna

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:35.520
 use a namespace of nsroute, you still can say

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:38.400
 route colon, or you can also say nsroute.

00:08:38.400 --> 00:08:40.840
 And so you can see that in this example, right?

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:43.340
 We can go to the second view of route,

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:45.700
 or we can go to the second view of ns.

00:08:45.700 --> 00:08:48.680
 And so there's route, route is the way, one way in,

00:08:48.680 --> 00:08:51.840
 but nsroute is our own way in, in case we somewhere

00:08:51.840 --> 00:08:54.040
 have an application named route or something like that.

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:57.620
 And so this allows for a second way to access

00:08:57.620 --> 00:09:00.720
 these URLs using a namespace.

00:09:00.720 --> 00:09:05.720
 And it's not in the urls.py in each application,

00:09:05.720 --> 00:09:09.400
 it is in the urls.py for the Django project.

00:09:09.400 --> 00:09:12.520
 So I just finished showing you all that in the templates,

00:09:12.520 --> 00:09:14.080
 but we can also do this in Python.

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:16.840
 And we'll find that sometimes in like models.py

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:20.200
 or views.py, or even sometimes in admin.py,

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:23.000
 we'll need to sort of be able to find a view

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:25.560
 in the same or another application

00:09:25.560 --> 00:09:28.080
 and automatically construct it.

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:31.360
 Sometimes in forms.py, we're gonna do it as well.

00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:35.600
 And so this, you tend to call this reverse or reverse lazy

00:09:35.600 --> 00:09:36.600
 to look these things up.

00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:39.920
 And the URL feature inside of the template

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:43.460
 is pretty much just calling this reverse lazy automatically

00:09:43.460 --> 00:09:45.600
 'cause the parameters are kind of the same.

00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:48.040
 So I just wanna show you how to do some of those things

00:09:48.040 --> 00:09:50.440
 that I just showed you in templates,

00:09:50.440 --> 00:09:54.880
 how you can do them in Python as well.

00:09:54.880 --> 00:09:56.040
 So here's the one in templates,

00:09:56.040 --> 00:09:58.460
 we just have this little plugin to a template

00:09:58.460 --> 00:09:59.920
 called the URL plugin.

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:03.400
 It takes one parameter and looks up in the urls.py

00:10:03.400 --> 00:10:06.480
 of the first application, the URL name, first view.

00:10:06.480 --> 00:10:08.360
 Maybe there's parameters, in this case there's not,

00:10:08.360 --> 00:10:13.360
 and then it generates a path to that /route/first, right?

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:16.180
 And so that's how you do it.

00:10:16.180 --> 00:10:19.240
 It's really under the covers calling this reverse lazy.

00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:21.480
 And so these reverse and reverse lazy

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:26.480
 are from the Django.urls library.

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:31.640
 And so in this view, there's nothing tricky about this view,

00:10:31.640 --> 00:10:33.880
 it's just a class-based view, we have a get method,

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:35.900
 we pass in all the request stuff.

00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:37.720
 But basically we can call reverse lazy

00:10:37.720 --> 00:10:39.440
 and pass it the exact same string,

00:10:39.440 --> 00:10:41.040
 this exact same string,

00:10:41.040 --> 00:10:43.480
 which is go into the gview application,

00:10:43.480 --> 00:10:45.880
 work your way down until you find the cats,

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:47.560
 or go into the gview application,

00:10:47.560 --> 00:10:49.560
 go in and find the one for dogs,

00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:52.680
 or in this case, this is the dog btail,

00:10:52.680 --> 00:10:55.300
 and it requires a number, and so this gview dog,

00:10:55.300 --> 00:10:59.120
 go find that one, and then the second parameter is 42,

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:00.860
 so make me one for that.

00:11:00.860 --> 00:11:05.420
 And in Python, u, u2, and u3 are all just strings,

00:11:05.420 --> 00:11:08.100
 which I'm passing in through some context,

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:10.360
 under the variables x1, x2, and x3.

00:11:10.360 --> 00:11:13.560
 They're really lousy choices of variable names,

00:11:13.560 --> 00:11:15.020
 but I do that sometimes to point out

00:11:15.020 --> 00:11:16.400
 that they're arbitrary and capricious,

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:18.120
 and all they have to do is match.

00:11:18.120 --> 00:11:21.680
 And so then like the x1 matches in this substitution,

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:23.440
 now we're just doing string substitutions,

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:26.000
 which is different than calling the URL,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:27.920
 but it's still just a bunch of strings.

00:11:27.920 --> 00:11:31.160
 You call reverse lazy in your Python code,

00:11:31.160 --> 00:11:33.560
 and now you're just pulling that string into

00:11:33.560 --> 00:11:35.020
 with double curly braces.

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:40.240
 And so this is how it ultimately works.

00:11:40.240 --> 00:11:41.840
 We can, you know, we get these,

00:11:41.840 --> 00:11:43.920
 we're just showing how this output turns out,

00:11:43.920 --> 00:11:47.440
 where we go reverse lazy for gview cats, gview dogs,

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:49.840
 or gview dog with an argument of 42.

00:11:49.840 --> 00:11:52.120
 We pass it in, we replace it,

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:54.400
 and so this is how it prints out gview cats,

00:11:54.400 --> 00:11:58.360
 slash gview dogs, slash gview dog 42.

00:11:58.360 --> 00:12:02.320
 And so that's how that reversing works in Python.

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:04.480
 And you'll see that certain situations,

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:05.560
 whether you're like in a model,

00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:06.520
 sometimes you're in a model,

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:08.920
 it's very common in a model to wanna put something

00:12:08.920 --> 00:12:10.680
 about the reverse in it.

00:12:10.680 --> 00:12:15.680
 And the reverse lazy says delay until later to look it up.

00:12:15.740 --> 00:12:20.240
 So up next, we're gonna put this all together

00:12:20.240 --> 00:12:23.480
 and ultimately start writing using the generic views

00:12:23.480 --> 00:12:25.960
 because we're gonna look at list pages and detail pages,

00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:27.960
 and in time, we're gonna look about delete pages

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:29.160
 and update pages.

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:31.360
 And Django has these wonderful features

00:12:31.360 --> 00:12:36.160
 that make it work really simply with very little code.

00:12:36.160 --> 00:12:37.320
 Well, we wanna talk about it

00:12:37.320 --> 00:12:40.400
 because sometimes the less code you write,

00:12:40.400 --> 00:12:41.860
 the harder it is to understand.

00:12:45.880 --> 00:12:48.460
 (upbeat music)

